## What I built

A Node.js/Express warehouse app with SQLite, server-rendered EJS UI, session auth, and role-based access.

**Core behavior — safe order processing:** `routes/orders.js` wraps the whole fulfillment in a single `better-sqlite3` transaction. It re-checks stock for every line item; if *any* product is short, it throws and the transaction rolls back — so an order is never partially fulfilled and stock can never go negative. The `quantity >= 0` CHECK constraint in the schema is a second line of defense.

**Roles:**
- `clerk` — view stock, process orders, view orders
- `manager` — all of the above **plus** add products and adjust stock levels

Enforced by `requireRole(...)` middleware on the manager-only routes (`/products/new`, `POST /products`, `POST /products/:id/adjust`).

## Files

```
package.json          dependency manifest
server.js             entry point, middleware, routes
db/connection.js      shared SQLite connection (WAL + foreign keys)
db/schema.js          users / products / orders / order_items tables
db/seed.js            demo users + products (idempotent)
middleware/auth.js    requireLogin / requireRole
routes/auth.js        login / logout (bcrypt-hashed passwords)
routes/products.js    stock view + manager-only management
routes/orders.js      transactional order processing
views/*.ejs           UI (login, dashboard, stock, orders, forms)
public/style.css      styling
README.md             run instructions
.gitignore
```

## How to run (port 5080)

```bash
npm install     # express, ejs, better-sqlite3, bcryptjs, express-session, connect-flash
npm run seed    # creates db/warehouse.db + demo users/products
npm start       # http://localhost:5080
```

Demo accounts: `manager / manager123` and `clerk / clerk123`. Port defaults to 5080 (override with `PORT=...`).

